31:"$Sreact.suspense"
0:{"buildId":"3_8tk2yXshjsX4BxM6gAi","rsc":["$","$1","c",{"children":[[["$","script",null,{"type":"application/ld+json","dangerouslySetInnerHTML":{"__html":"{\"@context\":\"https://schema.org\",\"@type\":\"Article\",\"headline\":\"GDPR Compliance for Developers: A Practical Guide\",\"description\":\"A practical GDPR guide for developers building SaaS applications. Covers data processing, consent, user rights, sub-processors, DPAs, and actionable steps.\",\"datePublished\":\"2026-03-16\",\"dateModified\":\"2026-03-16\",\"author\":{\"@type\":\"Organization\",\"name\":\"Codepliant\",\"url\":\"https://codepliant.dev\"},\"publisher\":{\"@type\":\"Organization\",\"name\":\"Codepliant\",\"url\":\"https://codepliant.dev\"},\"mainEntityOfPage\":{\"@type\":\"WebPage\",\"@id\":\"https://codepliant.dev/blog/gdpr-for-developers\"}}"}}],["$","article",null,{"className":"py-20 px-6","children":["$","div",null,{"className":"max-w-[680px] mx-auto","children":[["$","p",null,{"className":"text-sm font-medium text-accent mb-4 tracking-wide uppercase","children":"Blog"}],["$","h1",null,{"className":"text-4xl font-bold tracking-tight mb-4","children":"GDPR Compliance for Developers: A Practical Guide"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-sm text-muted mb-12","children":"Published March 16, 2026 · 15 min read"}],["$","div",null,{"className":"prose-custom space-y-6 text-base text-muted leading-relaxed","children":[["$","p",null,{"children":"GDPR has been in effect since May 2018, yet most developers still treat it as a legal problem rather than an engineering one. That is a mistake. The majority of GDPR obligations — consent management, data minimization, right to erasure, breach notification — are implemented in code. Your legal team writes the policies. Your engineering team makes them real."}],["$","p",null,{"children":"This guide is written for developers who build SaaS applications. It skips the legal theory and focuses on what you need to understand, what you need to build, and what you can automate. Whether you are retrofitting GDPR compliance into an existing product or building a new application from scratch, this article covers the practical engineering decisions you will face."}],["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-bold tracking-tight text-foreground pt-4","children":"GDPR core concepts developers need to understand"}],["$","h3",null,{"className":"text-xl font-bold tracking-tight text-foreground pt-2","children":"Controller vs. processor"}],["$","p",null,{"children":"This distinction determines your obligations. A data controller decides why and how personal data is processed. A data processor processes data on behalf of a controller. As a SaaS provider, you are typically both: a controller for data you collect about your users (analytics, billing), and a processor for data your customers store in your application (customer content)."}],["$","p",null,{"children":"This dual role has practical implications. For data you control, you must determine legal bases, set retention periods, and respond to user rights requests directly. For data you process on behalf of customers, your customers (the controllers) handle user rights, and you provide the technical mechanisms for them to do so — data export APIs, deletion endpoints, and access controls."}],["$","h3",null,{"className":"text-xl font-bold tracking-tight text-foreground pt-2","children":"Personal data is broader than you think"}],["$","p",null,{"children":"Under GDPR, personal data means any information relating to an identifiable person. This includes obvious identifiers like names and email addresses, but also IP addresses, cookie identifiers, device fingerprints, location data, and even pseudonymous data if it can be re-identified. In practice, almost all data your application collects about users qualifies as personal data."}],"$L2","$L3","$L4","$L5","$L6","$L7","$L8","$L9","$La","$Lb","$Lc","$Ld","$Le","$Lf","$L10","$L11","$L12","$L13","$L14","$L15","$L16","$L17","$L18","$L19","$L1a","$L1b","$L1c","$L1d","$L1e","$L1f","$L20","$L21","$L22","$L23","$L24","$L25","$L26","$L27","$L28","$L29","$L2a","$L2b","$L2c"]}],"$L2d","$L2e"]}]}]],null,"$L2f"]}],"loading":null,"isPartial":false}
2:["$","p",null,{"children":"Developers often underestimate this scope. Server logs containing IP addresses are personal data. Error tracking payloads that include user IDs are personal data. Analytics events tied to session identifiers are personal data. When in doubt, treat it as personal data."}]
3:["$","h3",null,{"className":"text-xl font-bold tracking-tight text-foreground pt-2","children":"Legal bases for processing"}]
4:["$","p",null,{"children":"GDPR requires a legal basis for every data processing activity. The six legal bases are: consent, contractual necessity, legal obligation, vital interests, public task, and legitimate interest. For SaaS applications, you will primarily use three:"}]
5:["$","ul",null,{"className":"list-disc list-inside space-y-2 ml-2","children":[["$","li",null,{"children":[["$","strong",null,{"children":"Contractual necessity:"}]," Processing needed to fulfill your service agreement. Storing user content, processing payments, sending transactional emails — all contractual necessity."]}],["$","li",null,{"children":[["$","strong",null,{"children":"Legitimate interest:"}]," Processing that serves a legitimate business purpose where the impact on the individual is minimal. Product analytics, security monitoring, fraud prevention — typically legitimate interest, but you must document a Legitimate Interest Assessment (LIA)."]}],["$","li",null,{"children":[["$","strong",null,{"children":"Consent:"}]," The individual explicitly agrees to processing. Marketing emails, non-essential cookies, and optional data sharing require consent. Consent must be freely given, specific, informed, and unambiguous."]}]]}]
6:["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-bold tracking-tight text-foreground pt-4","children":"What you need to build: the GDPR engineering checklist"}]
7:["$","h3",null,{"className":"text-xl font-bold tracking-tight text-foreground pt-2","children":"1. Consent management"}]
8:["$","p",null,{"children":"If you rely on consent for any processing activity, you need a system that records when consent was given, what the user consented to, how consent was obtained, and allows withdrawal at any time. For cookies, this means a cookie consent banner that blocks non-essential cookies until the user opts in. Do not use pre-checked boxes. Do not use \"by continuing to use this site you consent\" banners — these are not valid GDPR consent."}]
9:["$","p",null,{"children":"Technically, implement consent as a database record linked to the user: timestamp, consent scope, version of the privacy policy shown, and the user's choice. When consent is withdrawn, stop the associated processing immediately and record the withdrawal."}]
a:["$","h3",null,{"className":"text-xl font-bold tracking-tight text-foreground pt-2","children":"2. Data subject rights endpoints"}]
b:["$","p",null,{"children":"GDPR grants individuals several rights that your application must support. From an engineering perspective, these translate to API endpoints or admin tools:"}]
c:["$","div",null,{"className":"space-y-4","children":[["$","div","Right of access (Article 15)",{"className":"bg-surface rounded-xl p-5","children":[["$","h3",null,{"className":"font-semibold mb-1","children":"Right of access (Article 15)"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-sm text-muted","children":"Build a data export endpoint that compiles all personal data you hold about a user into a machine-readable format (JSON or CSV). This includes account data, usage logs, support tickets, and any derived data."}]]}],["$","div","Right to rectification (Article 16)",{"className":"bg-surface rounded-xl p-5","children":[["$","h3",null,{"className":"font-semibold mb-1","children":"Right to rectification (Article 16)"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-sm text-muted","children":"Allow users to update their personal data through your UI. Most SaaS apps already have profile editing, but verify it covers all personal data, not just name and email."}]]}],["$","div","Right to erasure (Article 17)",{"className":"bg-surface rounded-xl p-5","children":[["$","h3",null,{"className":"font-semibold mb-1","children":"Right to erasure (Article 17)"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-sm text-muted","children":"Build a deletion flow that removes personal data from your primary database, removes it from backups within a reasonable timeframe, propagates deletion to sub-processors, and maintains an audit log of the deletion itself (without the deleted data)."}]]}],["$","div","Right to data portability (Article 20)",{"className":"bg-surface rounded-xl p-5","children":[["$","h3",null,{"className":"font-semibold mb-1","children":"Right to data portability (Article 20)"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-sm text-muted","children":"Export user data in a structured, commonly used, machine-readable format. JSON is the standard choice. The export should include data the user provided directly (not derived analytics data)."}]]}],["$","div","Right to object (Article 21)",{"className":"bg-surface rounded-xl p-5","children":[["$","h3",null,{"className":"font-semibold mb-1","children":"Right to object (Article 21)"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-sm text-muted","children":"Allow users to opt out of processing based on legitimate interest. This typically means opt-out controls for analytics, marketing, and profiling."}]]}]]}]
d:["$","h3",null,{"className":"text-xl font-bold tracking-tight text-foreground pt-2","children":"3. Data minimization"}]
e:["$","p",null,{"children":"GDPR requires you to collect only the data you actually need. This is an engineering principle as much as a legal one. Audit every form field, every analytics event, and every API payload. Ask: do we need this data to provide the service? If not, do not collect it."}]
f:["$","p",null,{"children":"Common violations include collecting full names when only an email is needed for login, tracking granular user behavior when aggregate metrics would suffice, storing IP addresses indefinitely in server logs, and requesting broad OAuth scopes when narrow ones would work. Each unnecessary data point increases your compliance burden and your attack surface."}]
10:["$","h3",null,{"className":"text-xl font-bold tracking-tight text-foreground pt-2","children":"4. Breach notification system"}]
11:["$","p",null,{"children":"GDPR requires you to notify your supervisory authority within 72 hours of becoming aware of a personal data breach. If the breach poses a high risk to individuals, you must also notify affected users without undue delay. This means you need:"}]
12:["$","ul",null,{"className":"list-disc list-inside space-y-2 ml-2","children":[["$","li",null,{"children":"Monitoring and alerting for unauthorized data access"}],["$","li",null,{"children":"An incident response plan with clear ownership and procedures"}],["$","li",null,{"children":"Templates for authority and user notifications"}],["$","li",null,{"children":"Logging sufficient to determine the scope of a breach"}]]}]
13:["$","p",null,{"children":"The 72-hour clock starts when you become \"aware\" of the breach, not when you discover the root cause. Having a documented incident response process is essential to meeting this deadline."}]
14:["$","h3",null,{"className":"text-xl font-bold tracking-tight text-foreground pt-2","children":"5. Data Processing Agreements (DPAs)"}]
15:["$","p",null,{"children":"Every sub-processor that handles personal data on your behalf needs a Data Processing Agreement. This is a legal contract, but developers need to be aware of it because adding a new third-party service means a new DPA is needed. Major services like AWS, Stripe, Vercel, and Sentry have standardized DPAs you can sign online. Smaller services may require negotiation."}]
16:["$","p",null,{"children":"Maintain a sub-processor register that lists every third-party service, what data it processes, where it is hosted, and the DPA status. Codepliant automatically detects your third-party services by scanning your codebase, giving you a starting point for this register."}]
17:["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-bold tracking-tight text-foreground pt-4","children":"Common GDPR implementation patterns for SaaS"}]
18:["$","h3",null,{"className":"text-xl font-bold tracking-tight text-foreground pt-2","children":"Soft delete with scheduled purge"}]
19:["$","p",null,{"children":"When a user requests deletion, soft-delete their account immediately (marking it as deleted and removing it from the application) but schedule the hard delete for 30 days later. This gives you a recovery window for accidental deletions while still honoring the erasure request promptly. After 30 days, a background job permanently removes all personal data and propagates deletion to sub-processors."}]
1a:["$","h3",null,{"className":"text-xl font-bold tracking-tight text-foreground pt-2","children":"Anonymization for analytics"}]
1b:["$","p",null,{"children":"If you need historical analytics but not individual-level data, anonymize records after a defined retention period. Replace user identifiers with random tokens, aggregate event data, and remove any fields that could enable re-identification. Truly anonymous data is outside GDPR scope entirely."}]
1c:["$","h3",null,{"className":"text-xl font-bold tracking-tight text-foreground pt-2","children":"Encryption at rest and in transit"}]
1d:["$","p",null,{"children":"While GDPR does not mandate specific security measures, it requires \"appropriate technical and organizational measures.\" Encryption at rest (AES-256 for databases and file storage) and in transit (TLS 1.2+ for all connections) are considered baseline. Most cloud providers handle this by default, but verify your configuration. Also consider field-level encryption for sensitive data like government IDs or health information."}]
1e:["$","h3",null,{"className":"text-xl font-bold tracking-tight text-foreground pt-2","children":"Audit logging"}]
1f:["$","p",null,{"children":"Maintain immutable audit logs for all access to personal data, data modifications, consent changes, and deletion operations. These logs serve as evidence of compliance during regulatory inquiries. Log the actor, action, timestamp, and affected data categories — but do not log the personal data itself."}]
20:["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-bold tracking-tight text-foreground pt-4","children":"International data transfers"}]
21:["$","p",null,{"children":"If you transfer personal data outside the EU/EEA (which most SaaS applications do if they use US-based cloud services), you need a legal mechanism for the transfer:"}]
22:["$","ul",null,{"className":"list-disc list-inside space-y-2 ml-2","children":[["$","li",null,{"children":[["$","strong",null,{"children":"EU-US Data Privacy Framework:"}]," If your sub-processor is certified under the DPF, transfers to that processor are covered. Major providers like AWS, Google Cloud, and Microsoft are certified."]}],["$","li",null,{"children":[["$","strong",null,{"children":"Standard Contractual Clauses (SCCs):"}]," The fallback mechanism for transfers to countries without adequacy decisions. Most DPAs from major providers include SCCs."]}],["$","li",null,{"children":[["$","strong",null,{"children":"Adequacy decisions:"}]," Transfers to countries the European Commission deems adequate (UK, Canada, Japan, South Korea, and others) require no additional safeguards."]}]]}]
23:["$","p",null,{"children":"For each sub-processor, verify which transfer mechanism applies and document it. Your privacy policy must disclose international transfers and the safeguards in place."}]
24:["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-bold tracking-tight text-foreground pt-4","children":"GDPR and AI: additional obligations for AI-powered SaaS"}]
25:["$","p",null,{"children":"If your SaaS uses AI, GDPR adds specific obligations on top of the standard requirements:"}]
26:["$","ul",null,{"className":"list-disc list-inside space-y-2 ml-2","children":[["$","li",null,{"children":[["$","strong",null,{"children":"Article 22 — Automated decision-making:"}]," ","Users have the right not to be subject to decisions based solely on automated processing that significantly affect them. If your AI makes decisions about access, pricing, content moderation, or eligibility, you must offer human review."]}],["$","li",null,{"children":[["$","strong",null,{"children":"Transparency about AI processing:"}]," Your privacy policy must disclose the existence of automated decision-making, provide meaningful information about the logic involved, and explain the significance and consequences for the user."]}],["$","li",null,{"children":[["$","strong",null,{"children":"Data sent to AI providers:"}]," If you send user data to OpenAI, Anthropic, or other AI APIs, this is a data transfer to a sub-processor. You need a DPA with the AI provider, and the transfer must be disclosed in your privacy policy."]}],["$","li",null,{"children":[["$","strong",null,{"children":"Training data:"}]," If user data could be used to train AI models (either by you or your AI provider), this requires a separate legal basis — typically consent. Most major AI providers now offer options to opt out of training data usage."]}]]}]
27:["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-bold tracking-tight text-foreground pt-4","children":"GDPR enforcement: the numbers developers should know"}]
28:["$","p",null,{"children":"GDPR enforcement is real and increasing. As of 2026, regulators have issued over 2,000 fines totaling more than 4.5 billion EUR. While headline fines target large companies (Meta: 2.5 billion EUR, Amazon: 746 million EUR, TikTok: 345 million EUR), small and mid-size companies are fined regularly too. The median fine is around 50,000 EUR — significant for a startup."}]
29:["$","p",null,{"children":"Common violations that result in fines include:"}]
2a:["$","div",null,{"className":"space-y-4","children":[["$","div","Insufficient legal basis for processing",{"className":"bg-surface rounded-xl p-5","children":[["$","h3",null,{"className":"font-semibold mb-1","children":"Insufficient legal basis for processing"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-sm text-muted","children":"The most common violation. Typically results from relying on legitimate interest when consent is required, or processing data without any documented legal basis."}]]}],["$","div","Inadequate privacy notices",{"className":"bg-surface rounded-xl p-5","children":[["$","h3",null,{"className":"font-semibold mb-1","children":"Inadequate privacy notices"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-sm text-muted","children":"Vague, incomplete, or inaccessible privacy policies. Regulators check whether your privacy policy accurately reflects your data practices."}]]}],["$","div","Non-compliant consent mechanisms",{"className":"bg-surface rounded-xl p-5","children":[["$","h3",null,{"className":"font-semibold mb-1","children":"Non-compliant consent mechanisms"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-sm text-muted","children":"Pre-checked consent boxes, consent bundled with terms of service, cookie banners that track before consent is given."}]]}],["$","div","Failure to honor data subject rights",{"className":"bg-surface rounded-xl p-5","children":[["$","h3",null,{"className":"font-semibold mb-1","children":"Failure to honor data subject rights"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-sm text-muted","children":"Not responding to access or deletion requests within the required one-month timeframe, or providing incomplete responses."}]]}],["$","div","Insufficient security measures",{"className":"bg-surface rounded-xl p-5","children":[["$","h3",null,{"className":"font-semibold mb-1","children":"Insufficient security measures"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-sm text-muted","children":"Data breaches caused by inadequate security, especially where basic measures like encryption or access controls were missing."}]]}]]}]
2b:["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-bold tracking-tight text-foreground pt-4","children":"Action plan: GDPR compliance for your engineering team"}]
2c:["$","ol",null,{"className":"list-decimal list-inside space-y-3 ml-2","children":[["$","li",null,{"children":[["$","strong",null,{"children":"Scan your codebase."}]," Run Codepliant to generate an inventory of all data collection, third-party integrations, and AI usage in your application. This gives you the factual foundation for compliance."]}],["$","li",null,{"children":[["$","strong",null,{"children":"Document your data processing."}]," For each data category, record the legal basis, retention period, and sub-processors involved. This is your Record of Processing Activities (ROPA), required by Article 30."]}],["$","li",null,{"children":[["$","strong",null,{"children":"Implement user rights."}]," Build or verify data export, deletion, and consent management flows. Test them end-to-end, including propagation to sub-processors."]}],["$","li",null,{"children":[["$","strong",null,{"children":"Review your privacy policy."}]," Ensure it accurately reflects your data practices, names your sub-processors, specifies retention periods, and covers AI processing if applicable."]}],["$","li",null,{"children":[["$","strong",null,{"children":"Set up consent management."}]," Implement a GDPR- compliant cookie consent banner. Ensure non-essential cookies are blocked until opt-in."]}],["$","li",null,{"children":[["$","strong",null,{"children":"Prepare for breaches."}]," Document an incident response plan. Test it with a tabletop exercise. Ensure you can identify, assess, and report a breach within 72 hours."]}],["$","li",null,{"children":[["$","strong",null,{"children":"Integrate into CI/CD."}]," Add Codepliant to your deployment pipeline to regenerate compliance documentation on every deploy. This keeps your privacy policy synchronized with your code."]}]]}]
2d:["$","section",null,{"className":"bg-surface rounded-2xl p-8 text-center mt-16 mb-16","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-xl font-bold mb-3","children":"Automate GDPR compliance documentation"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted text-sm mb-6","children":"Scan your codebase to generate privacy policies, data inventories, and compliance documentation. Free, open source, no account required."}],["$","div",null,{"className":"bg-code-bg text-code-fg px-6 py-3 rounded-xl font-mono text-sm inline-block","children":"npx codepliant go"}]]}]
2e:["$","section",null,{"children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-bold tracking-tight mb-6","children":"Related resources"}],["$","div",null,{"className":"space-y-3","children":[["$","a","/gdpr-compliance",{"href":"/gdpr-compliance","className":"block bg-surface rounded-xl p-4 hover:ring-1 hover:ring-border-strong transition-shadow","children":[["$","h3",null,{"className":"font-semibold mb-1 text-sm","children":"GDPR Compliance Hub"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-xs text-muted","children":"Everything you need to know about GDPR compliance for your application."}]]}],["$","a","/blog/privacy-policy-for-saas",{"href":"/blog/privacy-policy-for-saas","className":"block bg-surface rounded-xl p-4 hover:ring-1 hover:ring-border-strong transition-shadow","children":[["$","h3",null,{"className":"font-semibold mb-1 text-sm","children":"How to Write a Privacy Policy for Your SaaS App"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-xs text-muted","children":"Step-by-step guide to creating a legally compliant SaaS privacy policy."}]]}],["$","a","/privacy-policy-generator",{"href":"/privacy-policy-generator","className":"block bg-surface rounded-xl p-4 hover:ring-1 hover:ring-border-strong transition-shadow","children":[["$","h3",null,{"className":"font-semibold mb-1 text-sm","children":"Privacy Policy Generator"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-xs text-muted","children":"Generate a privacy policy from your codebase in seconds."}]]}],["$","a","/data-privacy",{"href":"/data-privacy","className":"block bg-surface rounded-xl p-4 hover:ring-1 hover:ring-border-strong transition-shadow","children":[["$","h3",null,{"className":"font-semibold mb-1 text-sm","children":"Data Privacy Compliance Hub"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-xs text-muted","children":"Overview of all compliance frameworks Codepliant supports."}]]}]]}]]}]
